Hello everyone! Welcome to Tactics class!
RT is red, GM is purple, regular student is cyan
All the tactics we learn may be hard at first, but soon you will find it easy.
only English is allowed in classroom

claire, tunnet99, coco_yuang, pantrike, tieuphilac, Chancewu, civsnail, bomb, killer21st, nick_hopper, amitabha, FIFAWORLDCUP, yzhnie, Cloud, wetcat, aivo, yyfcsd, shuwang, Gl_buh, Padovan, L8RG8R, guminzhao, fallnavy, slamduk, scm2000, smiling, nhaanx, shaoping, vuquan, Ikon, Alan, luwenzhe, moocheng, swallow.
Many of you have downloaded the Tactics article called, "Space and Connections"
which one of you have read it?
a, i fogot to put the "i am here"button..:(((
Well, in that article, the importance of space move was discussed.
We will not repeat that topic here in class.
I hope one day you all can download it.
In the article "space and connections" the use and power of space move was explained.
But it did not explain why the space move sometimes is so good, but sometimes weak.
Today you will get answer to that question.
The topic of todays lesson is "Inner Structures".
The usefulness of a space move depends on inner structures.
The inner stones which most players consider irrelevant, actually bear the key role in any attack or defense.
i randomly pick one old game
Ok, I dont know if anyone of you knows this game or not..
but its not important who played..
mumax, this is not analyses class.
29 is a space move with building connections,
31 is a pure space move, closing up the 29 stone with h4 source.
it is not easy to answer.
We just feel its good, it looks good,
but hard to define the reason.
the setup of inner stones determine the strength of external stones
these are inner stones that make the 29 and 31 powerful.
If we could shuffle around the inside stones like the beginning of 'mah-jong' game, then it might turn out the 29 and 31 are silly moves,
Nakamura's strong side? using inner stones very powerfully?
because they dont have any support from inner stones.
If we switch stones 1 and 2 with each other,
then black likely cannot win this game
so small change, but big outcome
without stone 1, the h4 is nothing, and f6_g7 line weak
so, simply saying, if we could swap 1 and 2, then white is able to defend left side.
Of coure, in real renju this is impossible, so we just discuss it analytically
just to make you understand the importance of inner stone
ok, same position, 1 and 2 swapped.  right?
it is so much weaker now than before
white has probably many many ways to defend here
and the whole outcome was changed, just because we changed ONLY 1 stone DEEP inside the position
it means, the good location of inside stone can influence the future attack a lot.
yeah.only one stone.black 1 lose the connect.
The next example I picked randomly too
Its from the first WC, in 1989
In the old times, this 7th was the most popular...
Now, black played 21 - a space move.
Sometimes, we do not have good protection against them.
However, there is certain tactics of defense,
We just learned the importance of inner structures.
The good inner stone can be a good attacker, or good defender.
we do not necessarily need to follow the space move ..
Sometimes, it is enough, if we cut off the inner connection with space move,
and the space move becomes a lonely wolf,
having no power to do anything up there in the space
it is a good defender because if cut off all the support for space move
it is far enough from 21 so that it can create activity of its own
this is very IMPORTANT style for players who need to WIN (draw is not enough)
if we follow the stone 21 nearby, we might never win as white
Now, black realized the 21 alone in space is too weak, and black doesnt have time to put more stones into space there
because white has active area already.
White is using all the benefits of 22, and manipulates with earned tempo.
we just show the failure of space move
yes. but 22 is not so inner )))
from the aspect of 21, the 22 is inner
because, 22 stands between 21 and the rest of the stones
because of inner moves, 22 is strong enough to defend
furthermore, 22 is strongly supported by stones 2 and 4,
and wall is the strongest iner defender.
If, for example, black had more inner supportsm
then it is risky to play inner defense
because we risk to lose tempo and allow black make space even more powerful
but in this case, there is no other help coming for stone 21
and the basic rule of defense is:
"If you can choose between several defense moves, then choose the one which is the most useful for self"
hehe, I would like to choose most safety one
in short "always do the best possible move"???
and best defense is not the move that 'defends' most solidly, but the one that 'defends sufficiently' so that it cannot lose, while giving 'self maximum power'
in most cases you can not calculate everything clear.
yes but hard to use in reallity
From this point, black realizes that passive following of moves 22 and 24 will result with slow death,
so black attempted to give some support for stone 21,
and try to work out the space.
These moves carry the purpose of k8 support only.
And now, it may look scary for a second,
And we are tempted to follow the space.
Space stones without support are easy to fail!!
White has so tight wall around those 3 stones
and despite both black pairs are open,
The rest of the moves in this game are not important, black died soon..
white controls both h11 and h10 points
making the black space power worthless.
So, those we already became big fans of space moves after the article "space and connections", beware, that your inner structures are good enough to carry out your ideas in the space.
space with no inner connection means dead @@
Wow,your net speed is too quickly..

pantrike, tieuphilac, claire, slamduk, Cloud, FIFAWORLDCUP, civsnail, guminzhao, aivo, killer21st, luwenzhe, shaoping, Chancewu, Ikon, amber, Alan, nick_hopper, wetcat, yyfcsd, yzhnie, vuquan, Padovan, bomb, fallnavy, swallow, smiling, shuwang, L8RG8R, amitabha, eastmen, coco_yuang, dadisheng, tunnet99, Gl_buh, scm2000, moocheng.
lack of inner support means, opponent stones are standing better
and when we think of every space move like beginning the new game in another area
then it becomes very important whose stones are helping the "new game"
For example, we might like i7 as black in usual case..
But now, having the same 3 stones in center,
because black gets weak support from upper area
we may call it a theory.
It was very popular in the past
until other 16th moves became more popular.
In one of my articles in the past, I analysed 16-f5.
It was an interesting response to the black's space move.
it was really a sufficient defense,
however, it required lots of defense skill and preciseness.
In my game with Nikonov, I chose another 18th move, inspired by the tactics of inner structures.
At that time, such move was usually considered a bad move.
The common understanding of tactics among renju players at that time was:
dont make inside move, its a waste!
It is still popular teaching phrase nowadays.
The analysis of "inner structures" was unknown at that time.
Therefore, my 18th move was considered as a surprise.
It is seemingly a weak move, even risky..
for those people, suppose to be a surprise
But I had it all counted.
the inner stone was followed by an aggression by white
and that way not giving black any time to enjoy the space
in relation to the four that can be formed?
3 white pairs, isnt that enough agrressive?
and even k12 support as the 4th pair
white get tempo for some time..
Black faces same situation as in last diagram:
would the tempo be sufficient to develop the pairs?
To follow whites means slow death (or even fast),
So the only chance is to try to make some good out of this space idea.
i think of g8 e8 f7
If black had played to g8,
it would waste all black power
and all the space idea would be failed
so, to keep up the only hope for win, black continued the space battle
So you counted all this at 18?
This was the end of the game.
21 looks strong but it is bad calculation
The 18 was the inspiration during game..
I was not sure I had win before he made 19, 21
I hoped the innder defense is tight enough
so that he cannot get enough support.
He nearly got some support through k8,
but that was not hard to be taken care of.
one must see the next stone 20,or he could't choose this 18 i think.right?
Yes, I aimed to point 20 when I made 18
But I was not sure if I can win in case of 21,
I played on the intuition that inner power is good enough for cut off blacks.
I hoped him to play this way,
it would save me all the sweatting
Now, lets look one old theory variant..
Nowadays, the variant goes like this:
But in the old times, the 7th was different.
How many of you know this variant?
Moves from 7 until here are all logical.
f11 now maybe,.. but then f9 maybe
Black does not have good positional advantage here..
the right side, lower side, all are kind of weak and out of control..
So, it remains left and upper part for black,
without much hope of support from other areas.
In such cases, black always attempts to gain more power by space move.
White has to choose defense here,
but as tunnet already mentioned, the f9 is the best defense, because it most effectively weakens the power of stone 17.
This 18 is definitely the best move.
You may notice similar elements as before... wall, aggressive... etc
e10 seems maybe logic too.. but gives black time to devlop...
A wall is good in Go and Renju :)
and stone 18 has a great meaning, like most other inner defense moves:
it cuts off the space move from the rest of the areas, which means:
black can only go on in that hopeless space, without any chance to drag the game to other areas.
Because now all other areas are weak
and without any support from blacks.
If 18 was following  a space move,
We have seen this game played by 9 dan player..
move 18 might have been "better" in the meaning of blocking stone 17,
but in created "holes" in other parts
how about 19 d9 after the previous wall
Most players are still influenced by a space move
and make this kind of 18th move,
as you see, even 9 dan players still do it.
The black connections are always more dangerous than the space.
Therefore, a good inner move that blocks all supports and connections is good even if it is still far from the space move of opponwent.
the stones 5_15 are still helping the space.
The single connection without sufficient inner stones is not enough
We can allow many blacks up there
and we dont worry to lose
Here, surprisingly, it is hard to find a white defense move that could lose.
in the idea of not allowing black to reach right wing for future defense
white has many many defense moves again
although it looks scary  at first look.
It will take some time, experience, and continuous practice,
to sense the power of inner structures.
For example, a good practice is:
Set up the position, similar to this one
and then make the following moves, using the inner wall method..
and let your opponent try to win
at first, maybe you try here
then you notice you defended well..
then try next game, even more aggressive..
and see if you still defend
then you will start to understand that the good defense maybe the aggressive inner stone
that cuts of blacks from the rest of the area.
The last variant we will see today is from d3.

aivo, tieuphilac, killer21st, guminzhao, civsnail, Gl_buh, amber, Chancewu, slamduk, amitabha, L8RG8R, vuquan, swallow, FIFAWORLDCUP, Cloud, fallnavy, scm2000, nick_hopper, Alan, coco_yuang, pantrike, luwenzhe, yzhnie, shuwang, smiling, shaoping, eastmen, eastmen, Padovan, ASV777, tunnet99, dadisheng, yyfcsd, bomb, moocheng, wetcat.
Also, quite famous theoretical variant in the past.
Black, being cut off from the rest of the areas,
has to use only the lower area,
And as usually, a space move is a classical way to begin it.
Now, many people temp to close it from outside,
So, the passive following of a space move, such as 14-i6 , is usually bad.
The best move is the passive inner stone.
In order to have any chance in this game, black must continue the space development.
But thanks to good 14th move, white cut off most supports for the space.
Having made calm inner 14, white MUST stay calm for the rest of the moves,
and not to let black influence psychologically by space attack.
If you get scared, and follow blacks, then you will likely lose..
I made a quick analysis before today's lesson,
white has some interesting choices here.
we just proved the passive style fails.
if white puts 16-f4 then black is good.
Black defends on of the white lines,
and the remaining white power is not enough to win within this tempo
white managed to create an additional inner stone
cutting off the use of stone 1
as you see here, the stone 1 will play the key ro;e
After this 16. black lost the support of stone 1
then black has still al the space
and now k7 is good for white
black can no longer cut it actively
good inner stones 14 and 16 did a good job,
they cut off the space attempt of 13, 15
so many good ideas all togethert
As you saw from all the examples today,
the inner structures are much more important than most of us believed before.
And I urge you to think more over this piece of tactics,
we talked about how White can defend so far
and try to use it in your future games whenever possible.
Now, we will end the lesson, thank you all very much!
